{"id":"2210.04488","submitter":"Michael J. Feldman","authors":"David L. Donoho and Michael J. Feldman","title":"Optimal Eigenvalue Shrinkage in the Semicircle Limit","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Recent studies of high-dimensional covariance estimation often assume the\nproportional growth asymptotic, where the sample size $n$ and dimension $p$ are\ncomparable, with $n, p \\rightarrow \\infty $ and $\\gamma_n \\equiv p/n\n\\rightarrow \\gamma > 0$. Yet, many datasets have very different numbers of rows\nand columns. Consider instead disproportional growth, where $n, p \\rightarrow\n\\infty$ and $\\gamma_n \\rightarrow 0$ or $\\gamma_n \\rightarrow \\infty$. With far\nfewer dimensions than observations, the disproportional limit $\\gamma_n\n\\rightarrow 0$ may seem similar to classical fixed-$p$ asymptotics. In fact,\neither disproportional limit induces novel phenomena distinct from the\nproportional and fixed-$p$ limits. We study the spiked covariance model,\nfinding for each of 15 different loss functions optimal shrinkage and\nthresholding rules. Readers who initially view the disproportionate limit\n$\\gamma_n \\rightarrow 0$ as similar to classical fixed-$p$ asymptotics may\nexpect, given the dominance in that setting of the sample covariance estimator,\nthat there is no alternative here. On the contrary, our optimal procedures\ndemand extensive eigenvalue shrinkage and offer substantial performance\nbenefits. The sample covariance is similarly improvable in the disproportionate\nlimit $\\gamma_n \\rightarrow \\infty$. Practitioners may worry how to choose\nbetween proportional and disproportional growth frameworks in practice.\nConveniently, under the spiked covariance model there is no conflict between\nthe two and no choice is needed; one unified set of closed forms (used with the\naspect ratio $\\gamma_n$ of the practitioner's data) offers full asymptotic\noptimality in both regimes. At the heart of these phenomena is the spiked\nWigner model. Via a connection to the spiked covariance model as $\\gamma_n\n\\rightarrow 0$, we derive optimal shrinkers for the Wigner setting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Oct 2022 08:33:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-11"}
